🌐 How GitHub Pages Works
Static File Hosting:
GitHub Pages is a static file hosting service. It works like this:

Your HTML file (voice_checker_web.html) is stored on GitHub's servers
When someone visits your URL, GitHub sends the HTML file to their browser
The browser downloads and displays the file
All processing happens in the user's browser - not on GitHub's servers

┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  GitHub Pages (Static Hosting)                              │
│  - Just stores and serves the HTML file                     │
│  - No server-side processing                                │
│  - Like a file storage + delivery service                   │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
                           │
                           │ Sends HTML file
                           ▼
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  User's Browser (Chrome/Edge/Safari)                        │
│  ✅ Runs JavaScript code                                    │
│  ✅ Accesses microphone                                     │
│  ✅ Processes audio                                         │
│  ✅ Displays results                                        │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
🎤 Where Each Part is Processed:
1. File Delivery (GitHub's Servers):
GitHub Pages → Sends HTML file → User's browser
GitHub only stores and delivers the file
No computation happens on GitHub
2. User Interface (User's Browser):
// Runs in the browser
- Displays the form
- Handles button clicks
- Shows results
3. Microphone Access (User's Device):
// Browser API
navigator.mediaDevices.getUserMedia()
- Accesses user's microphone
- Captures audio locally
- No audio sent to GitHub
4. Speech Recognition (Google's Servers):
// Web Speech API
const recognition = new webkitSpeechRecognition();
This is the key part! When you speak:

Browser captures audio from microphone
Browser sends audio to Google's Speech Recognition API
Google's servers process the audio and return text
Browser receives the text and displays it
User speaks → Browser captures audio → Sends to Google API
                                              ↓
User sees results ← Browser processes ← Google returns text
5. Word Comparison (User's Browser):
// JavaScript running in browser
function similarityScore(word1, word2) {
  // Levenshtein distance algorithm
  // Runs entirely in the browser
}
All comparison logic runs locally
No data sent anywhere for this part
